{{Infobox court case | name=Lucasfilm v Ainsworth | court=[[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]] | date decided=27 July 2011 | full name=Lucasfilm Limited and others (Appellants) v Ainsworth and another (Respondents) | citations={{cite BAILII|year=2011 |court=UKSC |num=39 ||parallelcite=[2012] 1 {{abbr|AC|Appeal Cases}} 208}} | judges= | prior actions= | subsequent actions= | opinions= }}
'''''Lucasfilm Limited v Ainsworth''''' was a 2011 court ruling by the [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.supremecourt.uk/docs/UKSC_2010_0015_ps.pdf |title=The Supreme Court Press Summary |publisher=Supremecourt.gov.uk |date=2011-07-27 |accessdate=2011-07-30 }}{{Dead link|date=December 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=Lucasfilm>{{cite BAILII|litigants=Lucasfilm Ltd v Ainsworth |year=2011 |court=UKSC |num=39 |courtname=auto}}.</ref> The case concerned an intellectual property dispute over the production of Lucasfilm's [[Stormtrooper (Star Wars)|Stormtrooper]] costumes by model maker [[Andrew Ainsworth]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/news/870603-george-lucas-defeated-by-star-wars-helmet-man-andrew-ainsworth |title=George Lucas defeated by Star Wars helmet man Andrew Ainsworth |publisher=Metro.co.uk |accessdate=2011-07-30}}</ref> Mr Ainsworth argued that the helmets, which he continues to manufacture and sell, were functional props covered only by design right legislation, as opposed to Lucasfilm's assertion that they were sculptures or art which fall under copyright law.<ref name="The Lucasfilm empire strikes out">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/international-news/european/the-lucasfilm-empire-strikes-out/article2112181/ |title=The Lucasfilm empire strikes out |publisher=theglobeandmail.com |accessdate=2011-07-31 |location=Toronto}}</ref> Design right protection is retained for 15 or 10 years, copyright protection can last considerably longer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/film-news/8665299/Star-Wars-prop-maker-wins-right-to-sell-Stormtrooper-helmets-in-UK.html |title=Star Wars prop maker wins right to sell Stormtrooper helmets in UK |publisher=Telegraph |date= 2011-07-27|accessdate=2011-07-30 |location=London}}</ref>
== Case background == The Stormtrooper character first appeared in the film ''[[Star Wars Episode IV: A New Hope]]''. The character was conceived by George Lucas, designed by artist [[Ralph McQuarrie]], sculpted by from Liz Moore<ref>{{Cite web | last = DeBord | first = Jason | title = Facebook Hosts Ongoing Public Debate Over Original Sculptor Credit for Star Wars Stormtrooper | publisher = OriginalProp.com | date = March 16, 2011 | url = http://www.originalprop.com/blog/2011/03/16/facebook-hosts-ongoing-public-debate-over-original-sculptor-credit-for-star-wars-stormtrooper-andrew-ainsworth-or-liz-moore-brian-muir/ | accessdate = September 9, 2011 }}</ref> and [[Brian Muir (sculptor)|Brian Muir]],<ref>{{Cite web | last = DeBord | first = Jason | title = Star Wars "Prototype" Stormtrooper Helmets | publisher = OriginalProp.com | date = June 24, 2008 | url = http://www.originalprop.com/blog/2008/06/24/star-wars-prototype-stormtrooper-helmets/ | accessdate = September 1, 2011 }}</ref> and finally molded from the existing designs by Andrew Ainsworth. Before the case came to court, Ainsworth had sold replica Stormtrooper outfits online for many years causing [[Lucasfilm]] to sue for infringement of copyright.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.supremecourt.uk/docs/UKSC_2010_0015_Judgment.pdf |title=Judgement: Lucasfilm Limited and others (Appellants) v Ainsworth and another (Respondents) |publisher=Supremecourt.gov.uk |accessdate=2011-07-31 }}{{Dead link|date=December 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name="The Lucasfilm empire strikes out"/> Ainsworth did not defend the 2006 case in the US courts and [[Default judgment|defaulted]]. Accordingly, the [[United States District Court]] for the [[Central District of California]] gave summary judgement in favour of Lucasfilm, awarding a [[USD]] $20 million compensation.<ref>{{Cite press release|title=Lucasfilm Ltd. Wins Major Copyright Infringement Lawsuit Against Star Wars Stormtrooper Pirate |publisher=[[Lucasfilm, Ltd.]] |date=October 11, 2006 |url=http://www.lucasfilm.com/press/news/news20061011.html |accessdate=September 1, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110910135838/http://www.lucasfilm.com/press/news/news20061011.html |archive-date=September 10, 2011 }}</ref>
In the English courts, Lucasfilm was represented by [[Michael Bloch (barrister)|Michael Bloch QC]] and [[Jonathan Sumption, Lord Sumption|Jonathan Sumption QC]].<ref name=SCUK/>
== Court ruling == The Supreme Court ruled that the Stormtrooper helmets could not be considered a [[sculpture]] for the purposes of the [[Copyright, Designs and Patents Act 1988]]. On the issue of the justiciability of a foreign copyright claim, the court ruled that providing that there is [[in personam]] jurisdiction over a defendant, an English court does have jurisdiction in this area. On this point, the case was distinguished from ''[[Mozambique rule|British South Africa v Companhia de Mocambique]]'',<ref name="Mozambique">''[[British South Africa Co v Companhia de Moçambique]]'' [1893] {{abbr|AC|Appeal Cases}} 602, [[Judicial functions of the House of Lords|House of Lords]], (England and Wales).</ref> that expressed the general principle that English courts have no jurisdiction to entertain an action to determine title, where claims applied to foreign intellectual property rights.<ref name=SCUK>{{cite web |url=http://www.supremecourt.uk/docs/UKSC_2010_0015_Judgment.pdf |title=Judgement: Lucasfilm Limited and others (Appellants) v Ainsworth and another (Respondents) |publisher=Supremecourt.gov.uk |accessdate=2011-07-31 }}{{Dead link|date=December 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
As part of their conclusions on the justiciability question, Lord Walker and Lord Collins stated:<ref>''Lucasfilm v Ainsworth'' [2011] UKSC 39, [105].</ref> {{cquote|We have come to the firm conclusion that, in the case of a claim for infringement of copyright of the present kind, the claim is one over which the English court has jurisdiction, provided that there is a basis for in personam jurisdiction over the defendant, or, to put it differently, the claim is justiciable. It is clear that much of the underpinning of the [[Mozambique rule|''Moçambique'' rule]] and the decision in [[Potter v Broken Hill Proprietary Company Ltd|''Potter v Broken Hill Pty Co Ltd'']] <ref name="Potter">{{cite AustLII|HCA|88|1906|litigants=[[Potter v Broken Hill Pty Co Ltd]] |parallelcite=[http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/cases/cth/HCA/1906/88.pdf (1906)&nbsp;3&nbsp;CLR&nbsp;479] |date=20 March 1906 |courtname=auto}}</ref> has been eroded. All that is left of the ''Moçambique'' rule (except to the extent that it is modified by the Brussels I Regulation) is that there is no jurisdiction in proceedings for infringement of rights in foreign land where the proceedings are “principally concerned with a question of the title, or the right to possession, of that property".<ref name=Lucasfilm/>{{rp|at [106]}}}}
They went on further to state: {{cquote|The basis for what remains of the rule was said by the House of Lords in the ''Moçambique'' case to be that controversies should be decided in the country of the situs of the property because the right of granting it was vested in “the ruler of the country” and in the ''Hesperides'' case to be the maintenance of comity and the avoidance of conflict with foreign jurisdictions. It is possible to see how the rationale of the ''Moçambique'' rule can be applied to patents, at any rate where questions of validity are involved.<ref name=Lucasfilm/>{{rp|at [107]}}}}
