{{Speciesbox | name = Skywalker hoolock gibbon | image = | image_caption = | status = EN | status_system = IUCN3.1 | status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |author1= Fan, P.F.|author2= Turvey, S.T.|author3= Bryant, J.V.|title= ''Hoolock tianxing'' (amended version of 2019 assessment)|year= 2020|page= e.T118355648A166597159 |access-date= 27 July 2020}}</ref> | genus = Hoolock | species = tianxing | authority = Fan & al., 2017 <ref name="FanEtAl2017">{{cite journal|last1=Fan|first1=P-F|last2=He|first2=K|last3=Chen|first3=X|last4=Ortiz|first4=A|last5=Zhang|first5=B|last6=Zhao|first6=C|last7=Li|first7=Y-Q|last8=Zhang|first8=H-B|last9=Kimock|first9=C|last10=Wang|first10=W-Z|last11=Groves|first11=C|last12=Turvey|first12=S.T|last13=Roos|first13=C|last14=Helgen|first14=K.M|last15=Jiang|first15=X-L|title=Description of a new species of Hoolock gibbon (Primates: Hylobatidae) based on integrative taxonomy.|journal=American Journal of Primatology|volume=79|date=2017|issue=9999|pages=e22631|doi=10.1002/ajp.22631|pmid=28073165|issn=1098-2345|url=http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/1529319/}}</ref> | range_map = | range_map_caption = }}
The '''Skywalker hoolock gibbon''' or '''Gaoligong hoolock gibbon'''<ref name=scinews>{{cite web|url=http://www.sci-news.com/biology/new-species-skywalker-hoolock-gibbon-04533.html |title=Hoolock tianxing: New Species of Gibbon Discovered in Myanmar and China |date=2017-01-13 |access-date=2019-04-24 |author=Natali Anderson}}</ref> (''Hoolock tianxing'') is a [[primate]] in the [[gibbon]] family, [[Hylobatidae]]. It is one of three species of [[hoolock gibbon]] and was first described in January 2017 in the ''[[American Journal of Primatology]]''.<ref name="guardian">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2017/jan/11/new-species-of-gibbon-discovered-in-china |title=New species of gibbon discovered in China |first=Georgia |last=Brown|date= 11 January 2017|work=The Guardian }}</ref> Researchers estimate ''H. tianxing'' diverged from ''H. leuconedys'' roughly 490,000 years ago.<ref name=scinews/>
==Etymology== The Skywalker hoolock gibbon is named after [[Luke Skywalker]] from the [[Star Wars]] franchise, as the scientists who described it are fans of the franchise.<ref name="BBC">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-38576819 | work=BBC News| date=11 January 2017|title='Star Wars gibbon' is new primate species}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.nationalgeographic.com/2017/01/star-wars-skywalker-hoolock-gibbons-primates/|title=New Species of Primate Is Named After 'Star Wars'|date=2017-01-11|website=National Geographic News|access-date=2019-02-18}}</ref> The [[specific name (zoology)|specific name]] ''tianxing'' is the [[Pinyin]] [[transliteration]] of the [[Chinese language|Chinese]] terms 天 (''tiān'') meaning "heaven" and 行 (''xíng'') meaning "movement".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/tian|title=Tian {{!}} Chinese religion|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2019-02-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yourdictionary.com/xing|title=Xing dictionary definition {{!}} Xing defined|website=www.yourdictionary.com|access-date=2019-02-18}}</ref> The name is a reference to [[brachiation]], the main locomotory mode of gibbons, and derived from the text of the ''[[I Ching]]'', an ancient Chinese book of divination.<ref name="FanEtAl2017"/>
==Habitat== The Skywalker hoolock gibbon is found in the tropical forests of eastern [[Myanmar]] and the [[Yunan Province]] in southwestern [[China]].<ref name="BBC"/> About 200 individuals are estimated to live in China and an unknown number in Myanmar.<ref name="BBC"/>
